        <h3 data-uuid="accedf1d26864024ac05b34c6d92957f">Business
            Leaders</h3>
        <p data-uuid="9804ea5caad14c5989d92d7668e48bf7">Some business
            leaders became wealthy, powerful, and famous because of the business boom. <b><dfn title="Carnegie, Andrew">Andrew
            Carnegie</dfn></b> was one of the most admired businesspeople of the time. Born in
            Scotland, Carnegie came to the United States as a poor immigrant. As a teenager, he took a job with a railroad company and quickly worked his way up to the
            position of railroad superintendent.</p>
        <p data-uuid="ecac3f7205384d4a9949ff0ffdd7da5f">
            In 1873 he focused his
            efforts on steelmaking. Carnegie expanded his business by buying out
            competitors when steel prices were low. By 1901 Carnegie’s mills were producing
            more steel than all of Great Britain’s mills combined. Carnegie’s businesses
            succeeded largely through <b><dfn title="vertical integration">vertical integration</dfn></b>, or ownership of
            businesses involved in each step of a manufacturing process. For example, to
            lower production costs, Carnegie acquired the iron ore mines, coalfields, and
            railroads needed to supply and support his steel mills.<br />
        </p>
